				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$ \mathrm{PTR}=\mathbbm{I}\left\{\mathrm{age}\ge 40\&\mathrm{CVD}\ \mathrm{risk}\ge 10\%\right\} $$\end{document}PTR=Iage≥40&CVDrisk≥10%, where \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$ \mathbbm{I} $$\end{document}I indicates that treatment (statins) is recommended over the alternative (no statins) when the bracketed expression is true.

Assuming higher values of a continuous outcome are advantageous, an optimal PTR is one that recommends treatment when, conditional on a set of moderating biomarkers Z, the mean outcome under treatment μ(A = 1/2, Z) is greater than the mean outcome under control μ(A =  − 1/2, Z):
